<Page x:Class="Kerbal_Space_Progam_Tools.Pages.InterplanetaryHowToGuide"
      xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
      xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
      xmlns:mc="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/markup-compatibility/2006" 
      xmlns:d="http://schemas.microsoft.com/expression/blend/2008" 
      xmlns:local="clr-namespace:Kerbal_Space_Progam_Tools.Pages"
      mc:Ignorable="d" 
      d:DesignHeight="2500" d:DesignWidth="1180"
      Title="InterplanetaryHowToGuide">

    <Grid Background="#FFFDE7E7">
        <ScrollViewer Margin="0">
            <TextBlock x:Name="textBlock" TextWrapping="Wrap" Background="White"><Span FontWeight="Bold" FontSize="24" FontFamily="TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT"><Run Text="&#x9;&#x9;&#x9;&#x9;&#x9;Interplanetary How-To Guide "/></Span><Run FontStyle="Italic" FontSize="16" FontFamily="TimesNewRomanPS-ItalicMT" Text="by Kosmo-not"/><LineBreak/><Run FontStyle="Italic" FontSize="16" FontFamily="TimesNewRomanPS-ItalicMT"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" Text="So, you want to get to another planet. It's the same as going from Mun to Minmus."/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" Text="However, we're dealing with vast distances and higher velocities. It will take more"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" Text="precision to get there. This guide addresses getting from the orbit of one planet to the"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" Text="intercept of another planet using a Hohmann transfer."/><LineBreak/><LineBreak/><Run FontWeight="Bold" FontSize="14" Text="Assumptions:"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="OpenSymbol" Text="• "/><Run FontSize="14" Text="Planets are in circular orbits and not inclined."/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="OpenSymbol" Text="• "/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="TimesNewRomanPSMT" Text="The parking orbit of the spaceship is circular and not inclined."/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="TimesNewRomanPSMT"/><LineBreak/><LineBreak/><Run FontWeight="Bold" FontSize="14" Text="Section 1: Planetary Phase Angle"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" Text="It doesn't do much good to your delta-v budget if you launch at the wrong time. In fact,"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" Text="it could be disastrous, meaning you might not have any chance at returning home. To"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" Text="know the right time to launch the mission, you have to calculate a phase angle the two"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" Text="planets should have to each other (the angle from one planet to another with the sun at"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" Text="the vertex)."/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" Text="The process of calculating this phase angle is quite simple. First, we need to determine"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" Text="how much time it will take to transfer from one planet's orbit around the sun to the other"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="TimesNewRomanPSMT" Text="planet's orbit."/><LineBreak/><InlineUIContainer>
            		<Image
            			Width="155" Source="/Kerbal Space Progam Tools;component/Images/HowToGuide/Interplanetary How-to Guide_page_1_1.jpg" x:Name="image" Height="55"/>
            	</InlineUIContainer><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="Remember: the radii used are of the planet's orbits around the sun and the gravitational"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="parameter used is the sun's."/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="Next, we need to determine how far the other will travel (in degrees) during the time the"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="spacecraft is in transit. We calculate the angular velocity (°/s) and multiply it by the"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="transit time:"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI"/><Run Text=" "/><InlineUIContainer>
            		<Image
            			Width="105" Source="/Kerbal Space Progam Tools;component/Images/HowToGuide/math1.PNG" x:Name="image1" Height="60"/>
            	</InlineUIContainer><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" Text="Since the spacecraft travels through 180°, we can easily get the phase angle between"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="planets at the start of the transfer:"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="  "/><InlineUIContainer>
            		<Image
            			Width="255" Source="/Kerbal Space Progam Tools;component/Images/HowToGuide/maths2.PNG" x:Name="image2" Height="70"/>
            	</InlineUIContainer><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="For the purposes of this guide, positive values indicate the target planet starts out in"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="front. Negative values mean the target planet starts behind."/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI"/><LineBreak/><Run FontWeight="Bold" FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI"/><LineBreak/><Run FontWeight="Bold" FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="Section 2: Velocity"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="To get to the other planet, you need to know what velocity you need to achieve from the"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="planet you're currently orbiting around. This requires two steps: 1) Determine the"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="velocity difference between the velocity needed to get to the other planet's orbit and the"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="velocity of the current planet, and 2) The velocity needed at your current orbit to"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="achieve the needed velocity once out of the sphere of influence."/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="First, we calculate the change in velocity needed for the Hohmann transfer:"/><LineBreak/><InlineUIContainer>
            		<Image
            			Width="175" Source="/Kerbal Space Progam Tools;component/Images/HowToGuide/Interplanetary How-to Guide_page_2_1.png" x:Name="image3" Height="40"/>
            	</InlineUIContainer><LineBreak/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="We will need to be going that much faster than our planet of origin at the start of the"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="Hohmann transfer. The value just calculated is the velocity we need to be at just prior to"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="exiting the planet's SOI."/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="Using conservation of specific orbital energy, we can calculate the velocity needed at"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="our parking orbit to exit the SOI at the correct velocity (we'll refer to this as our ejection"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="velocity):"/><LineBreak/><InlineUIContainer>
            		<Image
            			Width="195" Source="/Kerbal Space Progam Tools;component/Images/HowToGuide/maths3.PNG" x:Name="image4" Height="65"/>
            	</InlineUIContainer><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="where:"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="r1 = parking orbit radius"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="r2 = SOI radius"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="v1 = ejection velocity"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="v2 = SOI exit velocity (absolute value)"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="μ = gravitational parameter of origin planet"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI"/><LineBreak/><Run FontWeight="Bold" FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="Section 3: Transfer Burn Point"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="Exiting the sphere of influence heading in the wrong direction would screw up"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="everything we've worked through in the last two sections. It would not only increase the"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="delta-v needed for a transfer, but also change the transfer time. You'll either have to"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="spend even more delta-v to salvage your situation, or suffer embarrassment as you miss"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="the target planet. Knowing when in your parking orbit to perform your ejection burn is"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="critical for interplanetary travel."/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="A lot of people will think { that's easy, just do the burn at midnight/noon.} That is"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="wrong. Your trajectory will be curved by the planet and can be off by around 30° from"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="your intended direction of travel."/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="I'm going to let you loose on these equations."/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="r = parking orbit radius"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="v = ejection velocity"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="μ = gravitational parameter of origin planet"/><LineBreak/><InlineUIContainer>
            		<Image
            			Width="135" Source="/Kerbal Space Progam Tools;component/Images/HowToGuide/Interplanetary How-to Guide_page_3_1.jpg" x:Name="image5" Height="200"/>
            	</InlineUIContainer><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="(have this value in degrees, not radians)"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="Ejection Angle = 180° - θ"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="This is the angle from your travel direction as your get farther from the planet to your"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="ejection burn point. Here is a picture to illustrate (planet prograde is the desired"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="14" FontFamily="Segoe UI" Text="direction of travel in this case):"/><LineBreak/><InlineUIContainer>
            		<Image x:Name="image6" Height="422" Width="600" Source="/Kerbal Space Progam Tools;component/Images/HowToGuide/Interplanetary How-to Guide_page_3_2.jpg"/>
            	</InlineUIContainer></TextBlock>
        </ScrollViewer>

    </Grid>
</Page>
